<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="6" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="5.[189,498,866,893]" box="[189,498,866,893]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,498,866,893]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,498,866,893]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Ecology and distribution</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[189,1399,913,1186]" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">
The largest populations of 
<taxonomicName box="[521,657,913,940]" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Melosiraceae" genus="Angusticopula" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Melosirales" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Ochrophyta" rank="species" species="chilensis">
<emphasis box="[521,657,913,940]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">A. chilensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
were found in mosses growing on cliffs next to a waterfall dominated by several species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="R.L.Lowe, P.Kociolek, J.R.Johansen, B.Van de Vijver, H.Lange-Bertalot &amp; K.Kopalova" authorityYear="2014" box="[575,730,948,974]" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Diadesmidaceae" genus="Humidophila" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Naviculales" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Ochrophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[575,730,948,974]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Humidophila</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Grev." authorityName="Grev." box="[746,1097,948,975]" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Achnanthaceae" genus="Diatomella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Achnanthales" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Ochrophyta" rank="species" species="balfouriana">
<emphasis box="[746,1025,948,974]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Diatomella balfouriana</emphasis>
Grev.
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="C. F. W. Carlson emend. Van de Vijver &amp; Goeyers. The" authorityName="Van de Vijver &amp; Goeyers. The" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Achnanthaceae" genus="Achnanthes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Achnanthales" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Ochrophyta" rank="species" species="muelleri">
<emphasis box="[1156,1399,948,974]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Achnanthes muelleri</emphasis>
C.F.W.Carlson emend. Van de Vijver &amp; Goeyers. The
</taxonomicName>
latter species are all known to thrive mostly in aerophilic, moist environments (
<bibRefCitation author="Van de Vijver" box="[571,874,1019,1045]" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Van de Vijver" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" pagination="1 - 412" refId="ref13960" refString="Van de Vijver B., Frenot Y. &amp; Beyens L. 2002. Freshwater diatoms from Ile de la Possession (Crozet archipelago, Subantarctica). Bibliotheca Diatomologica 46: 1 - 412." type="journal article" year="2002">
Van de Vijver 
<emphasis box="[744,802,1019,1045]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">et al.</emphasis>
2002
</bibRefCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName box="[895,1175,1019,1045]" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Melosiraceae" genus="Angusticopula" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Melosirales" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Ochrophyta" rank="species" species="chilensis">
<emphasis box="[895,1175,1019,1045]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Angusticopula chilensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was also found on several sub-Antarctic islands located in the southern Indian Ocean such as Iles Crozet (
<bibRefCitation author="Van de Vijver" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Van de Vijver" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" pagination="1 - 412" refId="ref13960" refString="Van de Vijver B., Frenot Y. &amp; Beyens L. 2002. Freshwater diatoms from Ile de la Possession (Crozet archipelago, Subantarctica). Bibliotheca Diatomologica 46: 1 - 412." type="journal article" year="2002">
Van de Vijver 
<emphasis box="[189,248,1089,1115]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">et al.</emphasis>
2002
</bibRefCitation>
), Iles Kerguelen (
<bibRefCitation author="Van de Vijver" box="[531,834,1089,1115]" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Van de Vijver" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" pagination="28 - 36" refId="ref13915" refString="Van de Vijver B., Ledeganck P. &amp; Beyens L. 2001. Habitat preferences in freshwater diatom communities from subantarctic Iles Kerguelen. Antarctic Science 13: 28 - 36. https: // doi. org / 10.1017 / s 0954102001000050" type="journal article" year="2001">
Van de Vijver 
<emphasis box="[707,765,1089,1115]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">et al.</emphasis>
2001
</bibRefCitation>
) and the Prince Edward Islands (
<bibRefCitation author="Van de Vijver" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Van de Vijver" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" pagination="795 - 808" refId="ref13997" refString="Van de Vijver B., Gremmen N. &amp; Smith V. 2008. Diatom communities from the sub-Antarctic Prince Edward Islands: diversity and distribution patterns. Polar Biology 31: 795 - 808. https: // doi. org / 10.1007 / s 00300 - 008 - 0418 - z" type="journal article" year="2008">
Van de Vijver 
<emphasis box="[189,248,1124,1150]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">et al.</emphasis>
2008
</bibRefCitation>
). The species was almost always incorrectly identified as 
<taxonomicName authorityName="C.A Agardh" authorityYear="1824" box="[1006,1112,1124,1150]" class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Melosiraceae" genus="Melosira" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Melosirales" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Ochrophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1006,1112,1124,1150]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Melosira</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. or 
<taxonomicName authority="C. Agardh." authorityName="C. Agardh." class="Bacillariophyceae" family="Melosiraceae" genus="Melosira" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Chromista" order="Melosirales" pageId="5" pageNumber="6" phylum="Ochrophyta" rank="species" species="varians">
<emphasis box="[1196,1398,1124,1150]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="6">Melosira varians</emphasis>
C.Agardh.
</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
